---
import BaseLayout from "@layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FurtherReading from "@components/FurtherReading.astro";
import BundleCta from "@components/BundleCta.astro";

const title = "About";
const description =
  "Why this archive exists, who Sanzo Wada was, and how to use the dictionary in real design work.";

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: title,
  description,
  url: new URL("/about", Astro.site).toString(),
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: "The Dictionary of Color Combinations",
    url: Astro.site?.toString(),
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <article class="about section">
    <div class="container-prose about__inner">
      <header class="about__header">
        <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
        <h1 class="text-balance">A modern dictionary for a 90-year-old idea.</h1>
      </header>

      <div class="prose">
        <p class="about__lede">
          In 1933, a Japanese painter named Sanzo Wada published a six-volume
          book cataloging 348 color combinations drawn from traditional Japanese
          dyes, textiles, and cultural practice. It became an underground
          reference for designers, fashion editors, and color-theory nerds for
          the next ninety years — precisely because it was
          <em>curated</em>, not generated.
        </p>

        <p>
          This site is an attempt to bring that curatorial spirit to the web.
          Not a palette generator. Not a library of infinite randomized swatches.
          A dictionary. With entries. With sources. With stories.
        </p>

        <h2>Who was Sanzo Wada?</h2>

        <p>
          Sanzo Wada (和田 三造, 1883–1967) was a painter, costume designer, and
          color researcher. He was trained in Western oil painting at the Tokyo
          School of Fine Arts, lived and studied in Europe, then returned to
          Japan where he spent decades documenting traditional color names and
          combinations from weaving, dyeing, printmaking, and costume. In 1953
          he won the first Academy Award for Best Costume Design for the film
          <em>Gate of Hell</em>.
        </p>

        <p>
          His <em>Dictionary of Color Combinations</em> (
          <span lang="ja">配色事典</span>) was a reference book, not a coffee-table
          object — each plate paired two or three colors and gave them context.
          It's out of print in the original, though Seigensha has republished
          portions of it.
        </p>

        <h2>Why not just copy the book?</h2>

        <p>
          Because that's not how copyright works, and it's not how good reference
          works either. Color values — the hex tuples themselves — are facts. They
          can't be owned. Traditional Japanese color names and the cultural knowledge
          around them have been in the public domain for centuries. But Wada's specific
          curatorial decisions, the sequence of plates, the editorial layout, and the
          Seigensha republication all have their own rights.
        </p>

        <p>
          So this archive is <em>inspired by</em>, not copied from. The combinations
          here draw on the same tradition Wada did — traditional shikisai (色彩) names,
          historical eras, and the underlying cultural context — but they are assembled
          independently. Over time, with proper sourcing, the full Wada catalog may find
          its way here too. For now: thirty carefully-chosen combinations, each rooted in
          the same tradition that inspired Wada, each documented and exportable.
        </p>

        <h2>How to use it</h2>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Designers:</strong> browse by mood or era, copy the hex list, and
            use as a starting point. Every palette has a documented historical context
            you can defend in a client review.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Developers:</strong> hit the Tailwind config and CSS variables export.
            The hex values work in any framework, any language.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Artists:</strong> the traditional Japanese names (with kanji and
            romaji) map to real pigments and dyes. Search the names to find historical
            references.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Writers + historians:</strong> each palette includes a description
            of when, where, and why these colors were used together.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What about the rest of the 348?</h2>

        <p>
          This is V1. The archive will grow. If you want to be notified when new
          palettes are added, sign up for the once-a-week newsletter on the
          <a href="/#newsletter">home page</a>. No spam. Just one palette, one era, one story.
        </p>

        <h2>Credits & ethics</h2>

        <p>
          The traditional Japanese color names used here are part of the cultural commons
          and have been in use for centuries. Historical context, descriptions, and
          curatorial decisions are original work. No images or text from Wada's book or
          its modern republications are reproduced here.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you're the rights holder of something you believe is reproduced here in error,
          please get in touch:
          <a href="mailto:hello@colorcombinations.org">hello@colorcombinations.org</a>.
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          &ldquo;Color is a power which directly influences the soul.&rdquo;<br />
          <span class="about__attribution">— Wassily Kandinsky, 1911</span>
        </blockquote>

        <p class="about__cta">
          <a href="/browse" class="btn btn-primary">Browse the archive →</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  {/* ============ FURTHER READING (affiliate) ============ */}
  <div class="about-library">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <FurtherReading
        title="Further reading"
        intro="Five books that shaped this archive — Wada's original, the Albers classic, and three shelf-defining histories of color. All five are worth owning."
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  {/* ============ BUNDLE CTA ============ */}
  <BundleCta variant="medium" />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about {
    padding-top: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 5rem);
  }

  .about__header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .about__header .eyebrow {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .about__lede {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw + 0.75rem, 1.25rem);
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-ink-900);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .about__attribution {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-500);
    font-style: normal;
  }

  .prose .about__cta {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .about-library {
    background-color: var(--color-paper-100);
    border-block: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
</style>
